    <part id="apis-and-ai">
      <title>APIs and AI: It's complicated</title>
      <slide id="api-ai-new-york">
        <title>(How) does AI affect APIs?</title>
        <img src="apis-and-ai-cover.jpg" title="How does AI affect APIs? Expert Opinions from API Days New York 2025" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6ekEQR45IIo" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ai-success">
        <title>AI <q>Success</q> Stories</title>
        <img src="cover-state-of-ai-in-business-2025.png" href="https://nanda.media.mit.edu/ai_report_2025.pdf" title='Aditya Challapally, Chris Pease, Ramesh Raskar, and Pradyumna Chari, "The GenAI Divide: State of AI in Business 2025", MIT NANDA, July 2025' style=" height : 30% ; float: right ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; " class="shadow" />
        <img src="cover-state-of-ai-2025.png" href="https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/quantumblack/our-insights/the-state-of-ai" title='Alex Singla, Alexander Sukharevsky, Lareina Yee, and Michael Chui, "The state of AI in 2025: Agents, innovation, and transformation", McKinsey, November 2025' style=" height : 30% ; float : right ; clear : right ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; " class="shadow" />
        <ul>
          <li>Necessary but not sufficient</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Building AI <em>solutions</em> well is necessary</li>
            <li>Establishing <em>connections</em> to capabilities is necessary</li>
            <li>Managing the <em>foundations</em> well is necessary</li>
          </ol>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-landscape-lifecycle">
        <title>The API Landscape Lifecycle for AI</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Not about single APIs → It's about the API landscape</li>
          <li>Lifecycle of evolving towards AI readiness</li>
          <ol>
            <li><link href="api-availability"/></li>
            <li><link href="api-description"/></li>
            <li><link href="api-search"/></li>
            <li><link href="workflow-apis"/></li>
            <li><link href="api-sandbox"/></li>
          </ol>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="api-availability">
      <title>Step #1: More APIs</title>
      <slide id="api-ai-evolution-1-more">
        <title>More APIs &amp; Tools</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-1-more.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="mcp-intro">
        <title>Model Context Protocol (MCP)</title>
        <img src="mcp-logo.png" style="float: right ; width : 20% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>MCP is the current <q>standard protocol</q> for LLM consumers</li>
          <li>The initial focus was on <em>additional and extended context</em></li>
          <ul>
            <li><em>Additional context</em> by providing access to the environment</li>
            <li><em>Extended context</em> by allowing MCP servers to externally manage context</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Many mapping tools generate MCP servers from OpenAPI descriptions</li>
          <li><em>What</em> to expose and <em>how to design it</em> is out of scope</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-mcp-ai-direct-idea">
        <title>MCP all the APIs</title>
        <img src="api-mcp-ai-direct.png" style="float: right ; height : 70% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; " />
        <ol>
          <li>Generate MCP from OpenAPI</li>
          <li>Publish/Install MCP servers for all APIs</li>
          <li>Consumers can access <em>all MCP tools</em></li>
        </ol>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-mcp-ai-direct-tradeoffs">
        <title>MCP all the APIs: Easy but Limited</title>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Pros:</em></li>
          <ul>
            <li>Zero development effort, many tools auto-generate MCP</li>
            <li>All APIs easily available</li>
            <li>Great for quick and focused experimentation</li>
          </ul>
          <li><em>Cons:</em></li>
          <ul>
            <li>Context window overflow happens quickly</li>
            <li>AI struggles with understanding workflows across endpoints</li>
            <li>Risk of misinterpreting MCP problems as general AI problems</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Good as a starting point but lacks sophistication and scalability</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="more-tools">
        <title>More Tools ⇏ Better Tools Landscape</title>
        <ul>
          <li>LLMs can now access many tools</li>
          <li>But they cannot understand many of them well</li>
          <li>Poor descriptions → poor tool selection → poor results</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="api-description"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="api-description">
      <title>Step #2: Better Described APIs</title>
      <slide id="ai-integration-api-ai-evolution-2-description">
        <title>Better Described APIs</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-2-description.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="dx-homework">
        <title>Do Your Developer Experience (DX) Homework</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Most API descriptions need quality improvements anyway</li>
          <li>Better descriptions benefit <em>everyone</em>, not just AI agents</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Complete and meaningful operation summaries</li>
            <li>Comprehensive examples for all operations</li>
            <li>Clear error handling</li>
            <li>Consistent terminology and naming</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Good DX is the foundation for good <em>agent experience (AX)</em></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="ax-homework">
        <title>Now There's AX Homework, Too</title>
        <img src="robot.png" style="float: right ; height : 80% ; margin : 0% 0% 0% 0% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>AI agents need information developers don't typically require:</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Everything that developers usually <q>just know</q></li>
            <li>Treat every API like an external one for developers with no context</li>
          </ul>
          <li>OpenAPI Initiative (OAI) might add AX-specific fields</li>
          <li>Until then, leverage description fields strategically</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-ai-readiness-score">
        <title>AI Readiness Score for APIs</title>
        <img src="api-ai-readiness-score-twilio-alarms.png"  href="https://jentic.com/scorecard" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="better-descriptions">
        <title>Better Descriptions ⇏ Scalable Tool Use</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Better AX reduces confusion and misuse</li>
          <li>But well-described APIs still can overload context</li>
          <li>The problem shifts from <em>understanding</em> APIs to <em>finding</em> the right ones</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="api-search"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
    <part id="api-search">
      <title>Step #3: Dynamic API Discovery</title>
      <slide id="ai-integreation-api-ai-evolution-3-search">
        <title>Dynamic API Discovery</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-3-search.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-tool-mapping">
        <title>One API ≠ One Tool</title>
        <img src="victorinox-swiss-champ-xxl.png" title="Victorinox Swiss Champ XXL" href="https://www.victorinox.com/de-DE/Produkte/Swiss-Army-Knife%E2%84%A2-and-Tools/Trades-and-Crafts/Swiss-Champ%C2%A0XXL/p/1.6795.XXL" style="float: right ; height : 72% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>APIs can be large and multifunctional</li>
          <li>Tools should be <em>task-specific</em></li>
          <li>AI rarely needs an entire API</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="github-api">
        <title>GitHub API</title>
        <img src="github-api.png" title="GitHub API" href="https://github.com/github/rest-api-description" style="float: right ; height : 72% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/github/rest-api-description">GitHub API</a></li>
          <ul>
            <li>11MB</li>
            <li>320k lines</li>
            <li>738 paths</li>
            <li>1114 operations</li>
            <li>259 webhooks</li>
          </ul>
          <li><a href="https://github.com/github/github-mcp-server">GitHub MCP Server</a></li>
          <ul>
            <li>19 toolsets (+3 remote)</li>
            <li>70 tools overall</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="dynamic-discovery">
        <title>Dynamic Discovery ⇏ Ideal API Landscape</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Discovery helps reduce tool overload</li>
          <li>Agents still have to invent workflows from scratch</li>
          <li>We need higher-level, business-aligned APIs</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="workflow-apis"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
    </part>
